NSW GOVERNMENT Gladys Berejiklian Premier of NSW MEDIA RELEASE 30 August 2021 Reducing Community Transmissions NSW Looks Towards Establishing a Cashless Society in 2022 Premier Gladys Berejiklian announced today that residents living in NSW will have to become accustomed to living differently to reduce the transmission of COVID19 Specifically she announced that cash transactions have been linked to increased community transmissions of COVID19 Residents should be prepared to conduct transactions using a virtual currency much like the digital currencies which have been successfully used in China NSW is now looking into a rollingout a system that eliminates the need for cash to conduct transactions within the state You can still have cash but it will not be accepted at most places in NSW once the rollout is complete Berejiklian said earlier today Most residents in NSW already use their debit or credit cards to purchase goods and services so moving towards a cashless society will be a seamless transition NSW Treasurer Dominic Perrottet has long argued for the move towards a cashless society after noting Chinas success in leading the world with cashless systems China is fast becoming one of the most cashless societies in the world fuelled by the rise of dominant fintech platforms like Tencents WeChat Pay and Alibabas Alipay In many cities across China it has become increasingly difficult to pay for a taxi buy groceries or even settle a bill at a restaurant without access to a mobile wallet After the Alpha phase rollout that is expected to occur in mid2022 residents of NSW will be expected to have transferred their money into a virtual wallet to purchase goods and services This virtual wallet will enable consumers to  Purchase staple items from all leading supermarkets in NSW  Conduct internet banking transactions  Pay for petrol at most service stations in NSW  Pay andor receive funds from all Australian Government agencies
